      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical R2023 R1 holds current ISO 9001 certification; FDA-validated solver version documented in model archive; version-controlled input decks stored in Git repository with tagged release.",
      "rationale": "The FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical R2023 R1) is commercially validated and ISO 9001 certified. All simulation input decks are version-controlled in a Git repository with a tagged release corresponding to this submission. Software QA documentation is on file."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems (beam bending, contact patch) reproduced to within 1% of analytical solutions using the same element formulations employed in the pedicle screw model.",
      "rationale": "Standard benchmark problems representative of the dominant physics (beam bending under combined axial-bending load, Hertzian contact) were solved and compared against analytical solutions. All benchmark results fell within 1% of the analytical reference, confirming correct code implementation for the element types used."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study demonstrates <2% change in all three QoIs between the production mesh and a mesh with 1.5× global refinement.",
      "rationale": "A systematic mesh convergence study was performed using three mesh densities (coarse, medium, fine). QoI values changed by less than 1.8% between the medium and fine meshes. The medium mesh was adopted as the production mesh, balancing accuracy and computational cost."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Force-displacement residuals converge to below 1×10⁻⁴ at every load step; energy balance error below 0.1%.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear solver convergence was monitored at every load increment. Force residuals converged to 3×10⁻⁵ and energy balance error remained below 0.05% throughout the loading history. No spurious oscillations or divergence events were recorded."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and post-processing scripts completed by a second analyst not involved in model construction.",
      "rationale": "An independent analyst reviewed the model setup, boundary condition definitions, contact pair assignments, and post-processing scripts against the simulation plan. No errors were identified. Review sign-off is documented in the model archive."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Constitutive model (bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V) validated against coupon tensile data; contact formulation (augmented Lagrange, frictional μ=0.3) justified by literature and sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "The bilinear isotropic hardening model for Ti-6Al-4V was calibrated against supplier-provided coupon tensile test data (n=5 specimens) and reproduced yield stress and ultimate tensile strength within 3%. Frictional contact (μ=0.3) was selected based on published tribological data for titanium-on-titanium interfaces and confirmed by a sensitivity study showing <4% QoI change over μ∈[0.2, 0.4]."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from lot-specific coupon tests; geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of test articles; uncertainty in inputs propagated via Monte Carlo (n=1000 samples).",
      "rationale": "Material properties (E, σ_y, σ_ult, tangent modulus) were obtained from lot-specific tensile coupon tests on the same Ti-6Al-4V bar stock used to manufacture the test constructs. Screw and rod geometry was measured by CMM on three representative specimens. Input uncertainty was propagated through the model using a 1000-sample Monte Carlo analysis, yielding QoI standard deviations of 2–4%."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N=11 constructs from production lot; CMM-verified geometry; traceability of material certificates documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from a single production lot. Each construct's screw and rod geometry was CMM-verified prior to testing. Material certificates were retained and cross-referenced to the simulation input parameters."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions replicate the intended COU loading environment; multiple load levels or construct configurations tested to bracket the design space.",
      "rationale": "Testing was performed under the single ASTM F1717 standard loading condition (static compression-bending at 5 mm/min crosshead rate, 35 mm offset). Only one test condition was applied; no variation in offset distance or loading rate was explored. This factor falls below the required level 3, representing a known limitation of the validation dataset. The shortfall is accepted given that the COU is similarly limited to the F1717 standard condition."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation boundary conditions, loading rate, fixture geometry, and environmental conditions match experimental setup to within documented tolerances.",
      "rationale": "The FEA model boundary conditions (fixed inferior block, displacement-controlled superior block at 5 mm/min equivalent quasi-static rate, 35 mm anterior offset) were set to match the ASTM F1717 test fixture geometry as measured by the testing laboratory. Fixture compliance was characterized and incorporated into the displacement boundary condition. Ambient temperature equivalency was confirmed (22±2°C)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric E/uval < 1.96 for all three QoIs; percent difference < 10% for each QoI relative to experimental mean.",
      "rationale": "All three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) satisfied both acceptance criteria: percent differences of 6.3%, 8.7%, and 5.1% respectively (all <10%), and E/uval values of 1.41, 1.78, and 1.02 respectively (all <1.96). The validation metric accounts for both model prediction uncertainty and experimental measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are mechanistically linked to the clinical failure modes (fatigue fracture, construct loosening) relevant to the COU.",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs are the standard ASTM F1717 performance metrics and are directly linked to the clinical performance of pedicle screw constructs under physiological bending loads. Construct stiffness governs load sharing with the vertebral column; yield force and force at 40 mm displacement characterize the onset and extent of plastic deformation relevant to fatigue life and revision surgery risk."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending, non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw, Ti-6Al-4V) is identical to the COU scenario; no extrapolation beyond validated geometry or loading mode.",
      "rationale": "The validation activities were performed on the exact device geometry, material, and loading configuration described in the COU. No extrapolation to different screw diameters, cannulation states, or loading modes is claimed. The validation domain fully encompasses the COU domain."
    }
